{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f61acb65-b6df-4e15-8a9e-cdd23620ad56","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests — so a \"scope\" is effectively the **entire app lifetime**. This means `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext is reused across all navigations, retaining its change tracker state.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — a new instance per injection. Simplest fix.\n\n2. **Manually manage scopes** using `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Clear the tracker** if you must keep scoped registration:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\n**TL;DR:** MAUI has no per-request scope like ASP.NET Core. `AddScoped` ≈ `AddSingleton` in MAUI. Switch to `AddTransient` for a fresh DbContext on each resolve.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"464d02eb-4480-48b6-ad1d-65fb26219d05","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scopes and `AddScoped` behavior. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly — no codebase exploration needed.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so `AddScoped` behaves effectively like `AddSingleton` — the same instance lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why the DbContext data \"persists\" across page navigations.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"100E:115126:1515EE8:17C3FA4:69FD3688"},"id":"3db7b50c-a6ef-4719-af95-91b27473b10e","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:04:18.165Z","parentId":"552221d5-a04a-47a3-b185-8354a9ca95c2"}
